Demand Estimation for Cars

Xiaochun Lai

Background

  • Environment
    • It is in early 2000s. A new U.S. car manufacturer, T (as a shorthand), is considering launching operations in Europe.
    • To make the important managerial decision, we need to estimate demand for cars and competitiveness of the car market in Europe.
  • Dataset
    • cars.csv includes sales, prices and observed attributes of cars.The sales record of each car model produced by existing car manufacturers in each European country between 1970 and 1999.
    • iron ore.csv records production level and prices of iron ore, which is the main input for car production. During the exercise, you may assume that the amount of iron ore used to produce each car model is proportional to the weight (we in cars.csv) of that model.
    • We dont really know the cost structures of the rival firms, neither do we have access to their customer records.
  • Variables
    • Variables ye, ma, and co are the keys of the dataset, representing year, market (country), and the car model, respectively.
    • Variables qu and pr represent sales quantity and price of the vehicle in the given market and year: qu measures the number of new car registered in the market in the year, and pr is denoted by the domestic currency.
    • Variables cy, hp, we, le, wi, he, li, sp, ac, and some others, measure attributes of the car model.

Analysis task

A. Use log-log Regression to estimate the relationship between quantity and price of cars B. Conduct Benefit Segmentation via Cluster Analysis of Conjoint Part-Utilities
C. Conduct a priori segmentation
D. Simulate market shares for different product-line market scenarios

#Set up
library("lfe")
## Loading required package: Matrix
library("data.table")

#Load data
cardata=fread("cars.csv",stringsAsFactors = F)
iron=fread("iron_ore.csv",stringsAsFactors = F)
iron=iron[iron$year<2000 & iron$year>1969]
iron$year = iron$year-1900

#combine table
cardata$ironProduction = NA
cardata$ironValue = NA
for (n in 1:nrow(cardata)){
    cardata$ironProduction[n] = iron$production[which(cardata$ye[n] == iron$year)]
    cardata$ironValue[n] = iron$unit_value_98[which(cardata$ye[n] == iron$year)]
}

Part A : Use log-log Regression to estimate the relationship between quantity and price of cars

  • Add Fixed variables to log-log regression
  • Add Control variables to log-log regression
  • Add Instrumental variables to log-log regression
#Construct Basic  log-log regression

#qu:sales quantity
#eurpr:price converted to Euros  to represent price
reg1=felm(log(qu)~log(eurpr),data=cardata)
summary(reg1)

#Scatterplot of prices and quantities
plot(cardata$eurpr,cardata$qu, main="Price vs Sales",
     xlab="Price", ylab="Sales", cex=2,cex.lab=1.5, cex.axis=1.5, cex.main=1.5, cex.sub=1.5)

#Add the regression line
pricespace=seq(0,50000,1000)
coef=reg1$coefficients
fitted=(exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*log(pricespace)))
lines(pricespace,fitted,col="blue",lwd=2)

Discovery 1. The regression line corresponds to the best linear predictor of sales quantity given price converted to Euros to represent price. in other words, exp(beta 0) is the demand (qu) when eurpr = 1

  • intercept(0): the intercept is 11.2904, which means the expected value (our best guess) of sales quantity is 11.2904 when the price is equal to 0. beta 0 is the level of log(qu) when eurpr =1.

  • coefficient(1): the coefficient is -0.2925, which means one percent change in the price in Euros would change sales quantity by -29.25 percent.(price elasticity of demand at any value of eurpr)

  1. The shape of the estimated demand looks unreasonable because its nearly flat. Also, we didnt consider control variables that influence both price and demand, fixed effects that control for latent demand-side factors, and instrumental variables that weight less on changes on P that are less correlated with cost changes. However, from the scatter plot we can see that there are more sales given lower price. (without accouting for other demand factors, not capture causal effect)

  2. The absolute value of coefficient is less than 1, which means the demand is inelastic, which means the total revenue increases when price increases.revenue is monotonically increasing in price- the optimal price is infinity

#Adding fixed effect
reg2=felm(log(qu)~log(eurpr)|factor(co):factor(ye)+factor(ma),data=cardata)

  • Location and time fixed effects
    • ye: year(=first dimension of panel)
    • ma: market(=second dimension of panel)
    • co: model code (=third dimension of panel)

Here We add the interactive effects between market and car model and year as fixed effects. Contamination arises from over-time variations (year). Through the data set we found that some attributes for car models in different year changed, e.g.he and ac. We suspect that both car models and yearly demand variations cause causality issues, so we include the interactive fixed effects between both car model and time. Also, different markets likely have different underlying demand and hence the firm has been offering different prices. After adding the fixed effects, the absolute value of coefficient becomes greater than 1, which is more reasonable.

#Add control variables
reg3=felm(log(qu)~log(eurpr)+loc+ac+he+engdpc|factor(co):factor(ye)+factor(ma),data=cardata)

  • Control Variables
    • loc: location code (production side country where producer produce model)
    • ac: time to acceleration (in seconds from 0 to 100km/h, some from 0 to 96km/h)
    • he: height (in cm)

Here we first test several attributes related to product attributes and consumer tastes, such as location code, time to acceleration,average of fuel efficiency and so on. Then, we find that lots of variables have high p-value and are not significant. We drop those variables and only keep loc, ac, and he which are significant. Consumers might have preferences for where the car model were produced, the time to acceleration and the height of the car. We found that consumers prefer cars with larger height and longer time to acceleration, which indicates consumer may prefer low-mid price cars which have larger height and longer time to acceleration than extreme luxury sport cars

  • engdpc: nominal GDP per capita in Euro (engdp/pop)

Also, we think that the macro environment and population also affects the purchasing power of consumers. Because price is also influenced by the inflation, here we want to use nominal GDP. The coefficient is positive, which means that with higher nominal GDP per capita in Euro, the sales quantity would be higher.

The amount of iron ore used to produce each car model is proportional to the weight. The prices of iron ore is the main input for car production. If the prices of iron ore increase, the input values of car will also increase, thus influence the prices of car. The iron ore price is highly related to costs. So, its a good IV here.

  • weironValue: weightprices of iron ore
    • Here we use the iron ore value times weight as the instrumental variable. The coefficient shifts from -1.46 to -4.29, which means that adding IV to the regression re-weight the price. iron ore value times weight is correlated with cost changes. The result with IV put more weights on changes in P that are highly correlated with cost changes.

  • Estimate the unit cost of cars
  • Find the pattern between price and costs

#Compare among 5 years, same car model, same market

#For example, year 84, car model alfa 33, market 1
#Access the values of control variables and fixed effects
loc = cardata[cardata$ye == 84 & cardata$ma == 1 & cardata$type == "alfa 33", ]$loc
ac = as.numeric(cardata[cardata$ye == 84 & cardata$ma == 1 & cardata$type == "alfa 33", ]$ac)
he = as.numeric(cardata[cardata$ye == 84 & cardata$ma == 1 & cardata$type == "alfa 33", ]$he)
engdpc = cardata[cardata$ye == 84 & cardata$ma == 1 & cardata$type == "alfa 33", ]$engdpc

fe = getfe(reg)
idc <- match('1',fe$idx)
fe_ma=fe[idc,1]
idc <- match('1.84',fe$idx)
fe_coye=fe[idc,1]
#Plug in the control variables and fixed effects in the demand function
demand = function(loc, ac, he, engdpc, fe_coye, fe_ma){
    demand = 0.0709*loc+0.1337*ac+0.102*he-0.0001989*engdpc+fe_coye+fe_ma
    
    return(demand)
}

constant = demand(loc, ac, he, engdpc, fe_coye, fe_ma)

#Optimize the profit with demand function by tuning the costs
profit = function(price){
    profit=-1*((price-4494)*exp(constant-4.291*log(price)))
    
    return(profit)
}

A specific pattern we found is that the cost-price ratio (cost/price) is 76.7% across years, markets, and car models.
This means that the demand is reasonable cause car companies will want to keep their products profitable for each car type though some type might have larger costs. Last but not least, 76.7% is a reasonable profitable ratio for low to middle price cars based on the reference of Toyotas 2021 gross margin.

  • Discovery:

    • The coefficient of log(avgurprrival) represents if the average rival price changes 1%,the quantity of my products would change caused what percentage, which also represents cross price elasticity of demand. In this regression, the coefficient means the sales of my products would increase about 4.6% if the average rival price increase 1%.

    • I expect a positive coefficient of the rival price,since the percentage increase of rival price should increase our sales somehow. So, the estimated coefficient fulfills my expectation in this aspect. But i also expect the coefficient of rival price would eliminate some contamination from the coefficient of our price. So,by adding average rival price, the coefficient of our price should change. But it doesnt change much, which means the log(avgurprrival) doesnt take the non-causal variations away from the coefficient of out price.

    • The estimated coefficient tell us that the competitiveness of the market is fierce, since the absolute value of coefficient of rival price and our price are almost the same, and the change of rivals price change has big impact on our demand. So, the competitiveness of market is fierce.
